This practical session has the following objectives:

Partial solutions will be provided for Exercises 3-5.

Exercise 1: Normal Distribution

1.1 Standard Normal

Many natural phenomena follow the normal distribution, whose probability density function is the familiar bell-shaped curve, symmetric about the mean \(\mu\). In addition, a celebrated theoretical result called the Central Limit Theorem says that the sampling distributions of sample means

\[\bar X =\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n X_i\]

say \(X_1,\ldots,X_n\)$ is a random sample of size \(n\) from a proper distribution and sample totals \(\sum_{i=1}^n X_i\) each are approximately normally distributed if the sample size \(n\) is sufficiently large. Since this theorem applies to almost all possible probability distributions from which a sample might be selected, including discrete distributions, the theorem brings the normal distribution into play in a wide variety of circumstances.

If \(X\) has a normal distribution with mean \(\mu\) and standard deviation \(\sigma\), and we define the standardization of \(X\) as

\[Z = \frac{X-\mu}{\sigma}\]

then \(Z\) is normally distributed with mean \(0\) and standard deviation \(1\), i.e., the standard normal distribution.

We write \(X \sim N(\mu,\sigma^2)\) to indicate that \(X\) has a normal distribution with mean \(mu\) and variance \(\sigma^2\) (or we could say with standard deviation \(\sigma\)). In this notation, the standard normal distribution is \(N(0, 1)\). The density function \(\phi(z)\) and cumulative distribution function \(\Phi(z)\).

In R, we can plot \(\phi(z)\)

y = seq(-5,5,0.01)
plot(y,dnorm(y,0,1),type="l",lwd=2,main="Standard Normal Density")

or

plot(y,dnorm(y),type="l",lwd=2,main="Standard Normal Density")

The default values of mean and variance are 0 and 1 respectively.

Determine the values \(\phi(0)\), \(\phi(1)\), and \(\phi(2)\).

The cumulative distribution function \(\Phi(z)\) can be plotted as well.

y = seq(-5,5,0.01)
plot(y,pnorm(y,0,1),type="l",lwd=2,main="Standard Normal cumulative distribution function")

or

plot(y,pnorm(y),type="l",lwd=2,main="Standard Normal cumulative distribution function")

Determine the values \(P(Z>0)\), \(P(Z>1)\), and \(P(Z>2)\).

The normal distribution is bell-shaped and symmetrically distributed about \(\mu\), which is also this distribution’s median and mode. Almost all of the probability is concentrated in the interval \(\mu \pm 3\sigma\). For example \(X\sim N(1,2^2)\), the probability \(P(\mu - 3\sigma\leq X\leq\mu + 3\sigma)\) is given by

mu = 1
sigma = 2
pnorm(mu+3*sigma,mu,sigma)-pnorm(mu-3*sigma,mu,sigma)

Determine also the probabilities \(P(\mu - 2\sigma\leq X\leq\mu + 2\sigma)\) and \(P(\mu - \sigma\leq X\leq\mu + \sigma)\).

We use \(z_\alpha\) to be the solution to the equation \(P(Z > z_\alpha) = \alpha\). This is the value on the horizontal axis that has area \(\alpha\) under the curve and to its right. For example, \(z_{0.05} = 1.645\). Approximately,

1-pnorm(1.645)

or we could find \(z_{0.05}\) directly by

qnorm(1-0.05)

Here we show the normal density function for a \(N(100,5^2)\) distribution

y = seq(80,120,0.1)
plot(y,dnorm(y,100,5),type="l",lwd=2)

If \(X\) has this distribution, the left shaded area of the following figure represents 95% of the area under the density function.

y = seq(80,120,0.1)
plot(y,dnorm(y,100,5),type="l",lwd=2)
yy = seq(80,qnorm(1-0.05,100,5),0.1)
polygon(c(yy,rev(yy)),c(dnorm(yy,100,5),rep(0,length(yy))),col='skyblue')

That is,

\[ P(Z\leq 1.645) = 0.95 \rightarrow P(\frac{X-\mu}{\sigma}\leq 1.645) = P(X\leq \mu+1.645\sigma) = P(X\leq 108.2243)= 0.95 \]

that the value \(x\) such that \(P(X\leq x)= 0.95\) could be also determined by

qnorm(1-0.05,100,5)

or

100+5*qnorm(1-0.05)
[1] 108.2243

One could also do the checking by computing

pnorm(108.2243,100,5)
[1] 0.9500007

or

pnorm((108.2243-100)/5)

Now, Let \(X\) be a \(N(20,4^2)\) random variable. Determine \(x\) that \(P(X>x)=0.025\). Further, compute the probability \(P(19\leq X\leq 21)\).

1.2 Calculating Normal probabilities

The normal distribution is very useful in modelling many different real world situations. The basic characteristics of the distribution are the same in each case - only the mean and standard deviation differ.

1.2.1 Mechanical component

The diameters of a mechanical component produced on a certain production line are known from experience to have a normal distribution with mean 97.5mm and standard deviation 4.4mm.

First, we plot the pdf.

set.seed(1400)
x<-rnorm(1000, mean=97.5,sd=4.4)
hist(x)

Denoting X be the diameter. Then X is distributed Normal(mean=97.5, sd=4.4)

  1. Find the proportion of components with diameter less than 90mm. Sketch it by hand for better understanding.

P(X<90)=pnorm(90,97.5, 4.4)= 0.0441.

px90=pnorm(90,97.5, 4.4)
px90

The proportion of components with diameter less than 90mm is about 4.4%.

  1. Find the proportion of components with diameter between 95 and 105mm. Sketch it by hand for better understanding.

P(95<X<105)=pnorm(105,97.5, 4.4) - pnorm(95,97.5, 4.4) = 0.6709.

pnorm(105,97.5, 4.4) - pnorm(95,97.5, 4.4)

The proportion of components with diameter between 95 and 105mm is about 67.09%.

  1. Find the proportion of components with diameter greater than 110mm. Sketch it by hand for better understanding.

P(X > 110)= 1 - P(X\(\le\) 110) = 1 - pnorm(110,97.5, 4.4) =0.0022.

1 - pnorm(110,97.5, 4.4)

The proportion of components with diameter greater than 110mm is about 0.22%.

Exercise 2: Graphical Display of Rugby Data

The data from this exercise are from games of rugby union. Typically, a game consists of bursts of activity which end when points are scored, or when the ball is moved out of the field of play, or when foul play occurs. The governing body for the sport makes occasional (minor) changes to the rules in the hope of promoting more continuous games. In order to investigate the effectiveness of these rule changes the length of time of passages of continuous play is often recorded during matches.

The data at hand concern lengths of time of passages of play for ten international rugby matches involving the New Zealand team (the `All Blacks’).

Exercise 3 Introduction to Programming: Writing simple functions in R

It’s often the case that we wish to carry out certain complex calculations or operations repeatedly. It would be tedious to have to write out the code to carry out those calculations or operations every single time inside an R Markdown chunk or in a script file. Indeed, you’ve been using just such sequences of calculations a lot, in the form of function. In this section, you’ll learn how to write simple functions.

Functions gather a sequence of operations into a whole, preserving it for ongoing use. Functions provide:

  • a name we can remember and invoke it by
  • relief from the need to remember the individual operations
  • a defined set of inputs and expected outputs
  • rich connections to the larger programming environment

As the basic building block of most programming languages, user-defined functions constitute “programming” as much as any single abstraction can.

Defining a function

Here’s a very simple function for converting from degrees Fahrenheit to Kelvin. (You might remember from chemistry that Kelvin is an absolute temperature scale.)

fahrenheit_to_kelvin <- function(temp_F) {
  temp_K <- ((temp_F - 32) * (5 / 9)) + 273.15
  return(temp_K)
}

We define fahrenheit_to_kelvin by assigning it to the output of function. The list of argument names are contained within parentheses. Next, the body of the function–the statements that are executed when it runs–is contained within curly braces ({}). The statements in the body are indented by two spaces, which makes the code easier to read but does not affect how the code operates.

When we call the function, the values we pass to it are assigned to those variables so that we can use them inside the function. Inside the function, we use a return statement to send a result back to whoever asked for it.

In R, it is not necessary to include the return statement. R automatically returns whichever variable is on the last line of the body of the function. Since we are just learning, we will explicitly define the return statement.

Questions

  1. Try out fahrenheit_to_kelvin on the freezing and boiling point of water. [Hint: F=32 for freezing, F=212 for boiling.]

  2. Write a function called kelvin_to_celsius that takes a value in Kelvin and returns that temperature in degrees Celsius. [Hint: To convert from Kelvin to Celsius, subtract 273.15.]

Combining functions

The real power of functions comes from mixing, matching and combining them into ever-larger chunks to get the effect we want.

Questions

  1. Define a function fahrenheit_to_celsius to convert directly from Fahrenheit to Celsius by reusing the two functions you have already created, and try it out on a few values.

  2. Modify your function so that it returns a character vector that contains the numerical value of the temperature followed the string “degrees Celsius”.

The sample function

Without going into the details of just how it works, the very useful R function sample simulates a finite random variable. The syntax is

sample(x, size, replace = FALSE, prob = NULL)

The inputs are:

x A vector giving the possible values that random variable can take; size How many random variates to simulate; replace A logical argument that specifies whether sampling is carried out with replacement; prob A vector giving the probabilities of the values in x. If omitted then the values in x are assumed to be equally likely.

Questions

  1. Simulate a sample of size 10 from the numbers 1 to 15 with and without replacement. What do you notice?
sample(1:15, size = 10, replace = TRUE, prob = NULL)
 [1] 14  9  7  3  8 14 12 15  9 14
sample(1:15, size = 10, replace = FALSE, prob = NULL)
 [1] 14  3 13  7 15 12  6  2 10  5
  1. Simulate a very large number of samples from the numbers 0 and 1 with replacement (of course!). What is the proportion of ones and zeroes you obtained?

Hint. Use table() command. Try ?table.

s1 = sample(c(0, 1), size = 1000, replace = TRUE, prob = NULL)
table(s1)
s1
  0   1

Exercise 5: 2 sample \(t\)-test

This exercise uses a study that was concerned the effect of Vitamin C on tooth growth in guinea pigs. The response is the length of odontoblasts (teeth) in each of 10 guinea pigs at each of three dose levels of Vitamin C (0.5, 1, and 2 mg) with each of two delivery methods (orange juice or ascorbic acid). For this example, we will ignore the different dose levels.

We first read in the data and store them as a dataframe tooth

tooth = read.csv(file="tooth.csv")
str(tooth)
'data.frame':   60 obs. of  3 variables:
 $ length  : num  4.2 11.5 7.3 5.8 6.4 10 11.2 11.2 5.2 7 ...
 $ delivery: chr  "VC" "VC" "VC" "VC" ...
 $ dose    : num  0.5 0.5 0.5 0.5 0.5 0.5 0.5 0.5 0.5 0.5 ...

Before we do any analyses we need to examine our data. With the analysis being considered, usually boxplot would give us a good feel for what is in our data.

boxplot(length ~ delivery, data=tooth)

Check the result of analysing this data using t-test. We are looking to see if there are differences in tooth length for the two delivery methods. Assuming that the variances are equal.

t.test(length ~ delivery, var.equal = TRUE, data=tooth)

    Two Sample t-test

data:  length by delivery
t = 1.9153, df = 58, p-value = 0.06039
alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group OJ and group VC is not equal to 0
95 percent confidence interval:
 -0.1670064  7.5670064
sample estimates:
mean in group OJ mean in group VC 
        20.66333         16.96333

An alternative way is to look at the ANOVA output

tooth.aov = aov(length ~ delivery, data=tooth)
summary(tooth.aov)
            Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)  
delivery     1    205  205.35   3.668 0.0604 .
Residuals   58   3247   55.98                 
---
Signif. codes:  0 ‘***’ 0.001 ‘**’ 0.01 ‘*’ 0.05 ‘.’ 0.1 ‘ ’ 1

Note the p-value of 0.06039 and the degrees of freedom are exactly the same as in the ANOVA output.

The bottom line is that doing a two-sample \(t\)-test assuming equal variance is the same as an ANOVA with only two groups to compare. What is the conclusion that you would make?

Summarise the hypothesis testing in 6 steps.
